   ['I am writing these things to you, hoping to come to you shortly;'],
   ['but if I am slow, that* you may know how men ought to conduct themselves in the house of God, which is the congregation* of the living God, the pillar and base of the truth.'],
   ['And confessedly great is the mystery of godliness*: God was manifested in the flesh, was justified in the spirit, was seen by messengers, was preached among the nations, was believed on in the world, was received up in glory.<font color=#808080></font><font color=#808080> {Footnotes: 1Ti 3:8,9,12,13- The Greek word is diakonos; &lsquo;deacon&rsquo; is the transliteration. This word </font>and its compounds in all other contexts are translated &lsquo;serve&rsquo;, &lsquo;servant&rsquo;, or &lsquo;service&rsquo; (see 3:10 &amp; 3:13). Because &lsquo;elder&rsquo; (&lsquo;overseer&rsquo; in Phil. 1:1) a known office of the congregation* is used, this context calls for an office or serving position in the congregation*. The actual word in Greek means &lsquo;servant&rsquo; who serves in reference to his job. The same word is used by Paul to describe a &lsquo;policeman&rsquo; (in modern terms) in Rom. 13:4. Context could also mean &lsquo;Those who minister,&rsquo; in general. Other Greek synonyms in the MLV are translated &lsquo;domestic servant&rsquo; &lsquo;attendant&rsquo; &lsquo;attendants&rsquo; &lsquo;minister*&rsquo; and &lsquo;bondservant.&rsquo;} '],
